Dreus</i>, <i>Drues</i> (nominative) and <i>Dru</i>, <i>Driu</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (accusative) and was introduced to England by the Normans. For further information about this name, see also   Montague  .","English: from the personal name <i>Drew</i>, a pet form of   Andrew   which was confused with the same name of Old French origin (see 1 above).","Irish: when not an adoption of the English surname, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Draoi</b> ‘son’ and ‘descendant of the druid’, from <i>draoi</i> ‘druid’, genitive <i>druadh</i> or <i>draoi</i>. All of these were often Anglicized as   Drury  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":44,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Drewe was born in 1338, in Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Drewe, was 38 and his mother, Eleanor de Kingston, was 28. He married Emma Cary Of Wiltshire in 1377, in Southampton, Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1437,